(From Daniel): What we ultimately want from these models is information about this relationship like this: \(biomass(type_i, pixel_j) \sim predictors_{ij}\)

However, we dont have \(biomass(type_i, .)\); we do have \(totalBiomass\) and \(cover(type_i, .)\). Even though the relationship between cover and biomass is not ideal at high cover value as we have discussed a little while ago, it may be what is available to us. This would look like: \(biomass(type_i, pixel_j) \sim biomassTotal(pixel_j) * allometricFraction(type_i, cover_i)\)

Instead of scouring the literature for such biomass ~ cover relationships for each of our 6 types, how would it work if we fit that relationship in the same model fitting as biomass ~ predictors? Along the lines of: \(biomassTotal(pixel_j) * allometricFraction(type_i, cover_i) \sim predictors_{ij}\)

We probably want a saturating relationship for allometricFraction(), potentially as simple as \(allometricFraction(type_i, cover) \sim a_i * cover / (b_i + cover)\)

Potentially, we could consider separate relationships for the non-tree types in the presence of trees (or simply in our forest ecoregion) to separate out understory conditions from real grasslands/shrublands.

Rewritten, this equation is \(biomassTotal(pixel_j) \sim predictors_{ij} *1/(a_i * cover / (b_i + cover))\)

To model this, we need to use a non-linear approach because of the nonlinear transformation of cover. Below is a basic attempt to fit a model using totalHerbCover and scaled climate and soils predictors. Because the response variable, biomass, is distributed between (0,Inf), I used a Gamma distribution with a log link as the model family. I also used the gnm R package.

# specify model with gnm --------------------------------------------------
#=( 1climate+2soils)f(cover;3,4)
# Here, climate and soils have linear effects (beta1, beta2) while beta3, beta4 are estimated through Nonlin().
# get data for tree cover, just for forest ecoregions
dat_herb <- dat %>% 
  filter(newRegion %in% c("eastForest", "westForest")) %>% 
  select(totalBiomass_MgHect, totalHerbCover, tmean_s, prcpTempCorr_s, isothermality_s, annWatDef_s,
         prcp_s, prcp_seasonality_s, prcp_dry_s, annWetDegDays_s,
         t_warm_s, t_cold_s, prcp_wet_s, soilDepth_s, sand_s, coarse_s,
         AWHC_s, clay_s, carbon_s, x, y, newRegion) %>% 
  drop_na() 
# make sure that total herb cover is > 0 
dat_herb[dat_herb$totalHerbCover==0, "totalHerbCover"]
## numeric(0)
# make sure that total biomass isn't 0 
dat_herb[dat_herb$totalBiomass_MgHect == 0, "totalBiomass_MgHect"] <- 
dat_herb[dat_herb$totalBiomass_MgHect == 0, "totalBiomass_MgHect"] + .00001

# do a log transformation of the response
# dat_herb <- dat_herb %>% 
#   mutate(totalBiomass_MgHect_logPlusConstant = log(totalBiomass_MgHect + 4))

# use a transformation of total biomass so the gamma model will fit
dat_herb[, "totalBiomass_MgHect"] <- dat_herb[, "totalBiomass_MgHect"] + 2

hist(dat_herb$totalBiomass_MgHect)

hist(dat_herb$totalHerbCover)

## use glm to get starting values for the gnm
glm_fit <- glm(totalBiomass_MgHect ~ tmean_s + prcpTempCorr_s +  isothermality_s + annWatDef_s + prcp_s +
                 prcp_seasonality_s + prcp_dry_s + annWetDegDays_s + t_warm_s + t_cold_s + prcp_wet_s + soilDepth_s +
                 sand_s + coarse_s + AWHC_s + clay_s + carbon_s + offset(log((totalHerbCover + median(totalHerbCover))/totalHerbCover)),
               data = dat_herb,
               family = Gamma(link = "log"))
# Then use coef(glm_fit) to initialize beta_j (for the linear terms) in your gnm start vector.

fit_gnm <- gnm(totalBiomass_MgHect ~ gnm::Mult(tmean_s + prcpTempCorr_s +  isothermality_s + annWatDef_s + prcp_s +
                           prcp_seasonality_s + prcp_dry_s + annWetDegDays_s + t_warm_s + t_cold_s + prcp_wet_s + soilDepth_s +
                           sand_s + coarse_s + AWHC_s + clay_s + carbon_s, gnm::Inv(totalHerbCover), (1 + offset(totalHerbCover))), 
               method = "gnmFit",
               start = c(coef(glm_fit)[1:18], 1, .5),
               #start = c(.1, rep_len(.1, length.out = 17), 1, 1),
               constrain = "gnm::Mult(tmean_s + prcpTempCorr_s + isothermality_s + annWatDef_s + prcp_s + prcp_seasonality_s + prcp_dry_s + annWetDegDays_s + t_warm_s + t_cold_s + prcp_wet_s + soilDepth_s + sand_s + coarse_s + AWHC_s + clay_s + carbon_s, gnm::Inv(.), 1 + offset(totalHerbCover)).totalHerbCover",
               constrainTo = .99,
               data = dat_herb,
               family = Gamma(link = "log"),
               iterMax = 2000
)
## Running main iterations....................................
## Done

See how the allometric fraction term looks with fitted coefficients

curve((.99 * x) / (coef(fit_gnm)[20] + x), from = 0, to = 100)

Here are predictions from this model using synthetic total herb cover data and mean values for each scaled climate and soils predictor:

# Predict using this model ------------------------------------------------
# Generate a sequence of cover values across observed range
cover_seq <- seq(min(dat_herb$totalHerbCover, na.rm = TRUE),
                 max(dat_herb$totalHerbCover, na.rm = TRUE),
                 length.out = 100)

# Create a new data frame for prediction
new_data <- data.frame(
  totalHerbCover = cover_seq,
  tmean_s = mean(dat_herb$tmean_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  prcpTempCorr_s = mean(dat_herb$prcpTempCorr_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  isothermality_s = mean(dat_herb$isothermality_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  annWatDef_s = mean(dat_herb$annWatDef_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  prcp_s = mean(dat_herb$prcp_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  prcp_seasonality_s = mean(dat_herb$prcp_seasonality_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  prcp_dry_s = mean(dat_herb$prcp_dry_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  annWetDegDays_s = mean(dat_herb$annWetDegDays_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  t_warm_s = mean(dat_herb$t_warm_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  t_cold_s = mean(dat_herb$t_cold_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  prcp_wet_s = mean(dat_herb$prcp_wet_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  soilDepth_s= mean(dat_herb$soilDepth_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  sand_s = mean(dat_herb$sand_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  coarse_s = mean(dat_herb$coarse_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  AWHC_s = mean(dat_herb$AWHC_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  clay_s = mean(dat_herb$clay_s, na.rm = TRUE),
  carbon_s = mean(dat_herb$carbon_s, na.rm = TRUE)
)

# Predict biomass on the response scale
new_data$predicted_biomass <- predict(fit_gnm, newdata = new_data, type = "response") - 2

# 5. Plot the predictions

plot(
  new_data$totalHerbCover,
  new_data$predicted_biomass,
  type = "l",
  lwd = 2,
  col = "blue",
  xlab = "total herb cover",
  ylab = "Predicted Biomass (Mg/ha)",
  main = "Effect of Cover on Biomass"
)

Here are maps of the raw biomass data, modeled total herb cover data, as well as the predicted biomass and the residuals (observed biomass vs.predicted biomass)

# plot the predictions and residuals --------------------------------------
# rasterize the biomass and total herb cover data
test_rast <-  rast("/Users/astears/Documents/Dropbox_static/Work/NAU_USGS_postdoc/PED_vegClimModels/Data_raw/dayMet/rawMonthlyData/orders/70e0da02b9d2d6e8faa8c97d211f3546/Daymet_Monthly_V4R1/data/daymet_v4_prcp_monttl_na_1980.tif") 
# rasterize total biomass in Mg/hect
dat_biomass_rast <- dat %>% 
  terra::vect(geom = c("x", "y"), crs = crs(test_rast)) %>% 
  terra::rasterize(test_rast, field = "totalBiomass_MgHect") %>% 
  terra::aggregate(fun = "mean", na.rm = TRUE, fact = 8)
## |---------|---------|---------|---------|=========================================                                          
# rasterize % total herb cover
dat_herbCover_rast <- dat %>% 
  terra::vect(geom = c("x", "y"), crs = crs(test_rast)) %>% 
  terra::rasterize(test_rast, field = "totalHerbCover") %>% 
  terra::aggregate(fun = "mean", na.rm = TRUE, fact = 8)
## |---------|---------|---------|---------|=========================================                                          
# generate predictions for this model using training data
# the 'total herb cover' term is called "totalHerbCover_term" in the dat_herb data.frame
# Predict biomass on the response scale
dat_herb$predicted_totalBiomass <- predict(fit_gnm, newdata = dat_herb, type = "response") - 2
# rasterize predicted total biomass in Mg/hect
dat_biomassPreds_rast <- dat_herb %>% 
  terra::vect(geom = c("x", "y"), crs = crs(test_rast)) %>% 
  terra::rasterize(test_rast, field = "predicted_totalBiomass") %>% 
  terra::aggregate(fun = "mean", na.rm = TRUE, fact = 8)
## |---------|---------|---------|---------|=========================================                                          
## calculate the residuals
dat_resids_rast <- (dat_biomass_rast - dat_biomassPreds_rast)/dat_biomass_rast * 100

## calculate the model predicted biomass for the target functional group
dat_funcGroupBiomassPred <- dat_biomassPreds_rast * (.99 * dat_herbCover_rast) / (coef(fit_gnm)[20] + dat_herbCover_rast)
  
# make plots 
plot_biomass <- ggplot() + 
  geom_spatraster(data = dat_biomass_rast) +
  labs(title = paste0("Observed total biomass from GEDI; Mg/hect")) +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "white",
                       high = "purple" , 
                       limits = c(0,2000),  na.value = "lightgrey") + 
  xlim(c(-2060750, 2555250)) + 
  ylim(c(-1895500, 972500))
## <SpatRaster> resampled to 500424 cells.
dat_biomassPreds_big <- dat_biomassPreds_rast %>%

  terra::as.points()

plot_biomassPreds <- ggplot() + 
    geom_spatraster(data = dat_biomassPreds_rast) +
